<DOC><DOCNO> AP881119-0013 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-88 0140EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Courts-Brennan     11-19 0284</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Courts-Brennan,0291</SECOND><HEAD>Brennan Helps Kick Off 200th Anniversary Of Federal Courts</HEAD><BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Supreme Court Justice William J. Brennan Jr.urged lawyers and judges to fight discrimination in an addresskicking off a yearlong celebration of the bicentennial of thefederal court system.   ``Much as we have made in the way of progress against racialdiscrimination, gender discrimination, enforcement of the Bill ofRights _ great as that progress has been _ there's still so muchstill to be done,'' Brennan said Friday.   The 82-year-old justice, who was appointed to the Supreme Courtin 1956 by President Dwight D. Eisenhower and is now its oldestmember, made a luncheon address to about 800 lawyers, judges andspectators.   Pennsylania Supreme Court Justice Robert N.C. Nix Jr. and 3rdU.S. Circuit Court of Appeals Justice A. Leon Higgenbotham Jr. bothpraised Brennan's 32 years on the high court and urged him againstconsidering retirement.   Brennan did not discuss his plans. He and Justice ThurgoodMarshall, who is also in his 80s and has said he does not intend toretire, are considered the court's leading liberals.   Brennan's appearance was sponsored by the Philadelphia BarAssociation and Federal Courts 200 Inc., which has organized aseries of events to mark the 200th anniversary of the creation ofthe federal court system next year.   The U.S. Constitution, adopted in 1787, provided for a SupremeCourt but gave Congress the authority to establish the federalcourts. On September 24, 1789, Congress passed and PresidentWashington signed legislation forming the Supreme Court, circuitcourts and district courts.   Federal Courts 200 plans mock trials, debate competitions andvarious festivities to mark the anniversary.</TEXT></DOC>